04690nam a22007215i 9780520920309DE-B159720230529094047.0m|||||o||d||||||||cr || ||||||||230529t20232023cau    fo  d z      eng d  a97805209203097 a10.1525/97805209203092doi  a(DE-B1597)542282  a(OCoLC)1153508679  aDE-B1597bengcDE-B1597erda0 aeng  acaucUS-CA 4aND497.Z6bA72 1999eb 7aART0150302bisacsh04a759.22211 aPressly, William L., eauthor.4aut4http://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/aut14aThe French Revolution as Blasphemy :bJohan Zoffany's Paintings of the Massacre at Paris, August 10, 1792 /cWilliam L. Pressly.  aReprint 2019 1aBerkeley, CA : bUniversity of California Press, c[2023] 4c©2023  a1 online resource (240 p.) :b1 frontisp.  atextbtxt2rdacontent  acomputerbc2rdamedia  aonline resourcebcr2rdacarrier  atext filebPDF2rda0 aCalifornia Studies in the History of Art. Discovery Series ;v600tFrontmatter -- tCONTENTS -- tIllustrations -- tPreface -- tIntroduction -- t1. A Checkered Career -- t2. The Journée of August 10,1792 -- t3. A Modern Bacchanal: Plundering the King's Cellar at Paris -- t4. The Furies of Hell: Celebrating over the Bodies of the Swiss Soldiers -- t5. Thesis and Antithesis: An Antiheroic Art -- t6. Counterrevolutionary Propaganda -- t7. Religious Transcendence -- tAppendix: Catalogue of Zoffany's Paintings of the French Revolution -- tNotes -- tSelected Bibliography -- tIndex0 arestricted accessuhttp://purl.org/coar/access_right/c_16ecfonline access with authorization2star  aWilliam Pressly presents for the first time a close analysis of two important, neglected paintings, arguing that they are among the most extraordinary works of art devoted to the French Revolution. Johan Zoffany's Plundering the King's Cellar at Paris, August 10, 1792, and Celebrating over the Bodies of the Swiss Soldiers, both painted in about 1794, represent events that helped turn the English against the Revolution.Pressly places both paintings in their historical context—a time of heightened anti-French hysteria—and relates them to pictorial conventions: contemporary history painting, the depiction of urban mobs in satiric and festival imagery, and Hogarth's humorous presentation of modern moral subjects, all of which Zoffany adopted and reinvented for his own purposes. Pressly relates the paintings to Zoffany's status as a German-born Catholic living in Protestant England and to Zoffany's vision of revolutionary justice and the role played by the sansculottes, women, and blacks. He also examines the religious dimension in Zoffany's paintings, showing how they broke new ground by conveying Christian themes in a radically new format.Art historians will find Pressly's book of immense value, as will cultural historians interested in religion, gender, and race.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 29. Mai 2023) 7aART / European.2bisacsh  aart devoted to french revolution.  aart historians.  aclose analysis of french paintings.  acontemporary history painting.  aconvey christian themes in new format.  acultural historians.  adepiction of urban mobs.  aheightened anti french hysteria.  ahogarths presentation of modern moral subjects.  ain satiric and festival imagery.  aplaces paintings in historical context.  areligious dimension in paintings.  aturn english against revolution.  avolume six.08iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertUniversity of California Press Package Archive Pre-2000z97831106353480 cprintz978052021196440uhttps://doi.org/10.1525/9780520920309?locatt=mode:legacy40uhttps://www.degruyter.com/isbn/9780520920309423Coveruhttps://www.degruyter.com/document/cover/isbn/9780520920309/original  a978-3-11-063534-8  University of California Press Package Archive Pre-2000b2000  aEBA_FAO  aEBA_UCA_YUP  aGBV-deGruyter-alles  aZDB-23-UCY